comments.name: RT210W
comments.text: L210W is a TAM that usually occurs in combination with M41L and T215Y. The combination of M41, L210W and T215Y causes high-level resistance to AZT and intermediate resistance to ABC and TDF.

comments.name: RT215SCDEIVALN
comments.text: T215Y/F are TAMs that causes intermediate/high-level resistance to AZT and potentially low-level resistance to ABC and TDF. T215S/C/D/E/I/V/N/A/L do not reduce NRTI susceptibility but arise from viruses that once contained T215Y/F. The presence of one of these revertant mutations suggests that the patient may have once been infected with a virus containing T215Y/F.

comments.name: RT98G
comments.text: A98G is a non-polymorphic accessory mutation associated with low-level reduced susceptibility to each of the NNRTIs.

comments.name: RT103N
comments.text: K103N is a non-polymorphic mutation that confers high-level reductions in NVP and EFV susceptibility. It is the most commonly transmitted DRM.

comments.name: RT179L
comments.text: V179L is a rare non-polymorphic mutation listed as a RPV-associated resistance mutation by the FDA package insert. Its effects on NNRTI susceptibility have not been well studied.

comments.name: RPVIntermediate
comments.text: This virus is predicted to have intermediate-level reduced susceptibility to RPV. The use of the combination of CAB/RPV should be considered to be contraindicated.
